{
  "answer": "In *The Wanderer* (ch. 11 of *Old English Elegies*), the speaker laments the loss of past glories amid ruined walls, asking:  \n\n> \"Hwǣr cwōm mægþumgyfa?\"[^1]  \n\n(translated: \"Where [has gone] the treasure-giver?\")  \n\nThis compound *mægþumgyfa* (\"treasure-giver\") is a near-equivalent to *beag-gyfa* (\"ring-giver\"), both evoking a lord as liberal distributor of precious gifts (*beag* = ring/arm-ring; *mægþ*/*maþþum* = treasure).[^2]  \n\nYes, rendering this simply as English \"lord\" would obscure the social structure invoked: the Anglo-Saxon *comitatus*, where a lord's authority rests on reciprocal bonds forged by \"streams of gifts\" to retainers (in exchange for loyalty and service in battle). \"Lord\" connotes mere hierarchy, muting this Germanic emphasis on gift-exchange as the engine of heroic society.[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), translation, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., transliteration: \"Hwaer cwom mearg? Hwaer cwom mago? Hwaer cwom maththumgyfa?\" [full chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/transliteration/).\n\n[^3]: Ibid., translation, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc) (context: earlier, the wanderer seeks a \"goldwine\" = gold-friend/giver, and \"sinces bryttan\" = treasure-dispenser). See also *Maxims I* (ch. 6): lords \"on heahsetle\" (high-seat) share the \"gifstol\" (gift-throne) as social ideal.[^4]\n\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 6 (*Maxims I*), translation, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-84cf09).",
